The study will use a pharmacokinetic-pharmacodynamic (PKPD) model that incorporates the Eleveld model and new pharmacodynamic parameters derived from frontal electroencephalography (EEG) in this population. The primary outcome measures will be the performance error (PE) and median absolute performance error (MDAPE), which will assess the accuracy of the predicted concentrations compared to the measured concentrations. Secondary outcome measures will include the median prediction error (MDPE), time of loss of response (LOR), time of burst-suppression (BS), and time of return of response (ROR). The study will enroll patients older than 65 years undergoing non-cardiac elective surgery and will be conducted as a single-group assignment with an open-label design.

The study will also evaluate the rates of other adverse drug events, length of intensive care and hospital stay, quality of life and health utility, and societal costs and cost-effectiveness/-utility. The study will enroll patients aged 18 years or older, and exclude those with other infectious diagnoses, surgically altered anatomy, or concurrent pancreatitis. The study will be conducted at multiple centers in the Netherlands, and the primary outcome measure will be the clinical cure rate by day 14 without relapse by day 30.

[/INST]  The provided clinical trial document outlines a prospective, randomized, double-blinded study to compare the effectiveness of conventional lung recruitment maneuvers versus ultrasound-guided lung recruitment maneuvers in morbidly obese patients undergoing laparoscopic bariatric surgery. The study will enroll 60 patients, randomly allocated into two equal groups: conventional (n=30) and ultrasound-guided (n=30). The study's official title is "Conventional Versus Ultrasound-guided Lung Recruitment Manoeuvre in Morbidly Obese Patients Underdoing Laparoscopic Bariatric Surgery: Prospective Randomized Clinical Study."

[/INST]  The study is a prospective, randomized, open-label trial conducted at the Department of Radiation Oncology at Masaryk Memorial Cancer Institute Brno (MMCI) to optimize the fractionation schedules of heel spur radiotherapy for pain relief. The study aims to determine whether a single fraction of radiotherapy is non-inferior to fractionated radiotherapy over a three-month period in terms of pain relief for heel spur patients.

The primary outcome measure is the non-inferiority of single fraction radiotherapy of heel spur compared to fractionated radiotherapy at 3 months after radiotherapy. Secondary outcome measures include the comparison of different single fraction radiotherapy prescriptions, the need for reirradiation till 1 year after radiotherapy, comparison of quality of life and VAS score at different time points, and the evaluation of individual parts of Calcaneodynia score and individual domains of quality of life. The study also aims to analyze the heel spur radiotherapy techniques in Czechia through a questionnaire survey.

[/INST]  The study compares the clinical outcomes and efficacy of single versus double pyloromyotomy during gastric per-oral endoscopic myotomy (G-POEM) for refractory and severe gastroparesis. The study is a randomized controlled prospective multicenter trial with 30 participants randomized into either the single pyloromyotomy or double pyloromyotomy group. The primary outcome measures include clinical success at 3, 6, and 12 months follow-up, GCSI score before and after GPOEM at 3, 6, and 12 months follow-up, technical success rate, total procedure time for each method, adverse events like pneumoperitoneum, gi bleeding, perforation, infection, and abdominal pain, and recurrence of symptoms. The study aims to evaluate the efficacy of double pyloromyotomy compared to single pyloromyotomy in G-POEM for the treatment of gastroparesis.

Keywords related to the study include SOD, Minayo Iron-rich Yeast Drink, and GSH.

[/INST]  The IDMet (RaDiCo Cohort) study is a national cohort study investigating the clinical, genetic, and biological characteristics of individuals with imprinting disorders (IDs) in both pediatric and adult populations. The study aims to identify the metabolic phenotype of IDs patients and its association with biological profiling, as well as determine the prevalence of metabolic abnormalities, risk for metabolic complications, and quality-of-life scores. The study will also evaluate different therapeutic approaches and identify a common base for all IDs. The study plan includes measuring the clinical, genetic, and biological characteristics of IDs patients, as well as searching for an association between the metabolic phenotype and biological profiling. The study will include adults and children with IDs, and will collect data over an average of 10 years.

[/INST]  The clinical trial titled "Unipolar Versus Bipolar Interlocking in Humeral Shaft Fractures in Adults" aims to compare the effectiveness of unipolar and bipolar interlocking techniques in the treatment of humeral shaft fractures in adults. The study will randomly assign participants to either the experimental unipolar group or the active comparator bipolar group. Both groups will undergo questionnaires and scanner assessments, including CT scans at months 9 and 12 to evaluate bone healing. The primary outcome measure is the proportion of patients with radiologically assessed bone healing at 12 months. The study is open-label, meaning that both the participants and the investigators are aware of the intervention. The study plan involves a parallel assignment design with no masking, and the primary purpose is treatment. The study includes a minimum age of 18 years and accepts participants of all sexes.

[/INST]  The study aims to investigate the effectiveness of a combined cognitive and social cognitive training program, delivered remotely, in improving cognitive function and motivation in individuals with early psychosis. The study will compare the outcomes of this intervention with a control group receiving standard early psychosis coordinated specialty care. The primary outcome measures will include changes in Test My Brain scores, Dysfunctional Attitudes Scale-Defeatist Beliefs Subscale (DAS-DB) score, Quality of Life Scale-Abbreviated, Behavioral Inhibition and Activation Scale (BIS/BAS) scores, and Motivation and Pleasure Scale-Self Report (MAPS-SR) scores. The study will provide valuable insights into the effectiveness of a combined cognitive and social cognitive training program in improving cognitive function and motivation in individuals with early psychosis, and may inform the development of more personalized and effective treatment approaches for this population.

[/INST]  The LA POPA trial is a randomized, controlled, superiority trial evaluating the effectiveness of Pit-picking surgery with Sinus Laser assisted Closure compared to Pit-picking surgery alone in treating pilonidal disease. The study includes adult patients aged 12 years and older with primary pilonidal sinus disease, and excludes those with certain medical conditions or cognitive impairments. The primary outcome measure is the success rate of treatment at 1 year, which includes the closure of all pits, absence of symptoms, absence of persisting sinuses, and absence of recurrence of pilonidal sinus disease. Secondary outcome measures include pain scores, patient-reported outcome measures, wound healing and complications, work rehabilitation, return to daily activities, recurrence rate, need for secondary or revision surgery, patient satisfaction, and quality of life. The study is conducted at multiple centers in a multicentre, single-blinded design.

[/INST]  The study aims to identify the sociodemographic, personal, and clinical characteristics of patients with substance use disorder (SUD) admitted to the Addiction Management Unit of Assiut University Hospital in Egypt. The study will gather information on patients' age, gender, marital status, work, income, educational level, and other demographic characteristics, as well as their previous admissions/trials for detox, medical, psychological, social, financial, and legal aspects of addiction, and adverse life events before starting addiction. Additionally, the study will assess personality traits using psychiatric interviews and standardized tools, and patterns of substance abuse through psychiatric interviews, Severity of Dependence Scale (SDS), and urine drug screen. The study will enroll all patients with SUD admitted to the Addiction Management Unit, and patients will be excluded if they refuse to participate in the study. The study will be conducted over one week, and the primary outcome measures will include identifying the sociodemographic characteristics of patients with SUD, identifying personality traits of patients with SUD, and identifying patterns of substance abuse among patients with SUD.

[/INST]  This is a clinical trial studying the use of immune checkpoint inhibitors and radioembolization for previously untreated metastatic hepatocellular carcinoma. The study is open-label, meaning that both the participants and the researchers know which treatment the participants are receiving. The study is designed as a single-arm phase 2 trial, meaning that all participants receive the same treatment. The primary outcome measure is the best objective response, which is defined as the percentage of participants who experience a complete or partial response to treatment. The study is also measuring the rate of abscopal effect, which is the rate of objective response of tumour sites outside the liver after radioembolization and immune checkpoint inhibitor therapy. Secondary outcome measures include progression-free survival, overall survival, incidence of treatment-related side effects, local control rate, and distant control rate. The study includes 120 participants and is expected to be completed in 3 years.

[/INST]  The study is a Phase II clinical trial evaluating the safety and efficacy of neoadjuvant durvalumab and tremelimumab in combination with gemcitabine and cisplatin in patients with intrahepatic cholangiocarcinoma that is borderline resectable/resectable but with high risk for recurrence. The study is open-label, meaning both the patients and the researchers know which treatment the patients are receiving. The study is designed as a single-group assignment, with all patients receiving the same treatment regimen. The primary outcome measure is the rate of conversion from unresectable to resectable tumors after neoadjuvant treatment, and secondary outcome measures include objective response rate, pathological complete response, overall survival, progression-free survival, rate of R0 resection, relapse-free survival, patient-reported outcomes, and event-free survival. The study is conducted at multiple sites, and patients are eligible to participate if they are aged 18 years or older, have histologically proven intrahepatic cholangiocarcinoma, and are not eligible for surgical resection with curative intent. The study excludes patients with hilar or distal cholangiocarcinoma, those who would not be surgical candidates due to reasons unrelated to their cholangiocarcinoma, and those with a history of autoimmune disease that has required systemic treatment in the past 2 years.

[/INST]  The study aims to evaluate the effectiveness of enhanced hippocampal neuroplasticity in surfacing inaccessible traumatic memories in veterans with post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD). The study will compare the results of hippocampal training combined with hyperbaric oxygen therapy (HBOT) to HBOT alone. The primary outcome measures will be changes in memory gaps and time to inaccessible memory surfacing, assessed through a traumatic scene form and daily questionnaires. Secondary outcome measures will include changes in brain activity as assessed by functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI), cognitive performance using Neurotrax, and memory test scores. [/INST]  The CuDOSIS trial is a clinical study investigating the use of 64Cu-DOTATATE PET/CT imaging for the diagnosis of cardiac sarcoidosis. The study aims to evaluate the sensitivity and specificity of 64Cu-DOTATATE in detecting macrophage infiltration in the heart, which is a hallmark of cardiac sarcoidosis. The study will enroll patients with clinically suspected or confirmed cardiac sarcoidosis, as well as patients with acute lymphocytic myocarditis, and compare the results to a control group of patients with neuroendocrine tumors. The primary outcome measures include the proportion of patients with tracer uptake in the heart on 64Cu-DOTATATE PET/CT and the 24-month rates of adverse outcomes. Secondary outcome measures include the distribution of tracer uptake in the heart and the comparison of tracer uptake between cardiac sarcoidosis and acute lymphocytic myocarditis.

[/INST]  The provided clinical trial document summarizes a study comparing the efficacy of inhaled sedation with sevoflurane versus current intravenous sedation practice in critically ill patients at high risk of acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS). The study aims to assess the primary outcome measure of PaO2/FiO2 ratio and secondary outcome measures, including progression to ARDS, rate of pneumonia, ventilator-free days to day 28, organ failure to day 5, mortality at day 28, length of ICU-stay up to 28 days, physiological measures such as oxygenation, PaCO2, pH, PEEP, plateau pressure, pneumothorax, switch from controlled to pressure-support ventilation, airway occlusion pressure, hemodynamic measures, acute kidney injury, supraventricular tachycardia, ICU-acquired delirium, and biomarker measurements. The study is designed as a randomized, parallel-group clinical trial with blinded outcome assessment and concealed allocation of patients at risk of developing ARDS to a strategy of inhaled sedation with sevoflurane or to a strategy of current intravenous sedation practice. The study will measure outcomes within 5 days from randomization and at day 28 or ICU discharge, whichever comes first.

[/INST]  The study is a clinical trial investigating the outcomes of different treatment modalities for massive rotator cuff tears. The study involves 120 patients aged 50-80 years who are randomly assigned to one of four treatment groups: arthroscopic rotator cuff partial repair with superior capsular augmentation with LHBBT, arthroscopic partial rotator cuff repair, arthroscopic complete rotator cuff repair, or conservative treatment. The primary outcome measures include changes in shoulder strength, range of motion, and functional scores (American Shoulder and Elbow Surgeons, Disabilities of the Arm, Shoulder and Hand, and Tampa Scale for Kinesiophobia) at pre-operative baseline, 6-months, 12-months, and 24-months follow-up visits. The study aims to determine the most effective treatment modality for massive rotator cuff tears.

[/INST]  The IRIS Program is a novel pathway designed to optimize the treatment of injection-related infections for people who inject drugs (PWID) in Hamilton, Ontario. The study is a single-group assignment, open-label design, with no masking. Participants in the intervention group will receive a one-stop, low-barrier combined care model that addresses their injection-related infections, including diagnosis and treatment of infections, substance use treatment, peer support, and care coordination/systems navigation. The primary outcome measures include the number of emergency department visits and hospital readmissions within 30 days of initial hospital admission or program enrolment, and the completion of intended course of treatment for the injection-related infection within 6 months of initial hospital admission or program enrolment. Secondary outcome measures include the number of hospital readmissions specifically for the infection, emergency department visits, new initiations or continuation of substance use treatment, mortality rates, and program drop-out and reasons for discontinuation. Eligibility criteria include age 16 or older, able to provide informed consent, presenting with a confirmed or suspected injection-related infection, history of injection drug use within 3 months of recruitment, and living in Hamilton, Ontario.

[/INST]  The study aims to investigate the impact of autonomic dysfunction on hemodynamic instability during per-oral endoscopic myotomy (POEM) in patients with achalasia. The study will enroll 30 patients, aged 19 years or older, who are scheduled to undergo POEM in Gangnam Severance Hospital. The patients will be divided into two groups based on their autonomic function: those with autonomic dysfunction and those without. The study will measure the wobble of systolic arterial pressure (SAP) during surgery as the primary outcome measure. The study will be conducted under general anesthesia, and the anesthesia will be standardized according to the institution's protocol. The study will run for 12 months, and the data will be analyzed using descriptive statistics and inferential statistics.

Inclusion criteria:

* Patients who are scheduled to undergo POEM in Gangnam Severance Hospital
* Patients aged 19 years or older
* Patients who are hemodynamically stable before surgery
* Patients who are able to read the informed consent form

Exclusion criteria:

* Patients who are hemodynamically unstable before surgery
* Pregnant women or breastfeeding women
* Patients who are unable to read the informed consent form

The study will measure the following primary outcome measures:

* Wobble of SAP during surgery

The study will also measure the following secondary outcome measures:

* Heart rate variability (HRV) test results
* Blood pressure changes during surgery
* Anesthetic depth monitoring

The study will enroll 30 patients, and the data will be analyzed using descriptive statistics and inferential statistics. The study will conclude after 12 months, and the results will be published in a peer-reviewed journal.

[/INST]  The study aims to evaluate the effectiveness of virtual reality glasses during inhaler treatment in children aged 2-5 years. The study is a prospective, single-blind, randomized, controlled trial conducted at a pediatric emergency department. Children who need inhaler treatment and meet the inclusion criteria are randomly assigned to one of three groups: VR audio-visual users (Roller Coasters, group 1), VR audio-visual users (Wild Dolphins, group 2), or no additional equipment (control group). The primary outcome measures are changes in pain scores, respiratory rate, oxygen saturation, and heart rate during and after inhaler treatment. The study includes 135 children and is powered to detect a 1% margin of error with 98% power.

[/INST]  The study is a clinical open trial evaluating the feasibility, acceptability, and effectiveness of a transdiagnostic psychological treatment, the Unified Protocol (UP-C/A), for children and adolescents with anxiety disorders and/or depression in routine primary care. The treatment is a 11-session group format, and parent training is offered simultaneously. Therapists are trained in the method and receive regular supervision. The study is conducted at two primary care clinics, and participants are screened using the Mini-International Neuropsychiatric Interview for children and adolescents (MINI-KID). Participants who fulfill inclusion criteria are informed about the project and are asked to provide self-report scales assessing emotion regulation, anxiety, and depression symptoms. Therapists are also asked to complete a scale assessing the feasibility and acceptability of the intervention. Data will be analyzed descriptively to answer research questions from self-reports from children, parents, and therapists regarding satisfaction with treatment, feasibility, and acceptability. Paired sample t-tests will be used to analyze primary and secondary outcomes. The study aims to recruit about 30 participants, and a sample size of about 20% of the sessions will be rated for compliance with the Unified Protocol.

[/INST]  The PALISA study is a clinical trial assessing the pain experienced by preterm infants during Less-Invasive-Surfactant-Administration (LISA). The study measures the median peaks per second of skin conductance (SC) during LISA and compares it to the N-PASS (Neonatal Pain, Agitation, and Sedation Scale) scores at various time points. The study also assesses the incidence of LISA failure, intubation, air-leaks, and intraventricular hemorrhage within 24 hours and 72 hours after LISA. The study also compares the SpO2/FiO2-ratio at baseline, 5 minutes after removal of catheter, and 60 minutes after LISA to skin conductance peaks per second. The study is designed to evaluate the relationship between skin conductance and pain in preterm infants during LISA.

The study will enroll 788 patients from high-volume specialist centers in Italy, with each center expected to perform at least 25 interventions per year. The primary outcome measures will be assessed at 6 months post-surgery, including the analysis of lymphadenectomy in relation to surgical radicalness, vascular anatomical variability, and mesocolic sail integrity. Secondary outcome measures will include vascular anatomical variability and the presence of middle colic artery and its branches. The study will use a common alpha-numeric code to collect data independently and anonymously from each center involved. Keywords related to the study include right hemicolectomy, colon cancer, and lymphadenectomy.

[/INST]  The study aims to investigate the effects of Cawthorne Cooksey exercises on balance and quality of life in children with hearing deficits. The study includes 89 children with severe acquired hearing deficits and 129 children with hereditary hearing deficits, who are randomly assigned to either the experimental group (Cawthorne Cooksey exercises) or the control group (Swiss ball exercises). The primary outcome measures are the Pediatric Berg Balance Scale and the Four-step square test, which are used to assess balance and stability at 12 weeks. The study findings suggest that Cawthorne Cooksey exercises may be an effective technique to improve balance and quality of life in children with hearing deficits.

[/INST]  The study aims to explore the psychological impact of Gestational Trophoblastic Neoplasia (GTN) on women after completing chemotherapy treatment. The study will investigate the emotional experiences and sources of support accessed by participants, and identify potential areas for improvement in the follow-up care provided to future patients.

The study will recruit 20 women who have completed chemotherapy treatment for GTN, and will conduct semi-structured telephone interviews to gather in-depth descriptions of their experiences. The interviews will be digitally recorded and transcribed verbatim. Thematic analysis will be used to identify common themes and interpret patient perspectives.

The study's inclusion criteria are:

* Treated with chemotherapy for a GTN diagnosis
* Completed treatment between 6 weeks and 24 months
* Able to provide informed consent
* No cognitive impairment

The study will not involve any medical or invasive procedures, and the risks associated with the project are minimal. Patients will be contacted via telephone to invite them to participate in the study, and independent analysis will be carried out separately before meetings are scheduled to discuss and ensure reliability of interpretations.

The study aims to gain insight into the patient perspective and improve the patient experience, and will involve the involvement of service users in the review of interview questions. The findings will be disseminated within the multidisciplinary team and presented at conferences.

[/INST]  The clinical trial evaluates the utility of bone grafts in open wedge corrective osteotomy and plate fixation in patients with malunited distal radius fractures. [/INST]  This clinical trial compares the effectiveness of digital and speculum exams for evaluating cervical dilation and effacement in preterm prelabor rupture of membranes (PPROM). The study is randomized controlled, with participants randomly assigned to receive either digital or speculum exams. The primary outcome measures include pregnancy latency, maternal chorioamnionitis, endomyometritis, maternal sepsis, maternal wound infections, maternal intensive care unit (ICU) admission, and maternal death. Secondary outcome measures include composite neonatal morbidity, length of neonatal intensive care unit (NICU) admission, need for respiratory support, neonatal sepsis, neonatal intraventricular hemorrhage, necrotizing enterocolitis, hypoxic ischemic encephalopathy, and neonatal pneumonia. The study aims to evaluate the safety and efficacy of digital exams in comparison to speculum exams for evaluating cervical dilation and effacement in PPROM.

[/INST]  The study is a single-center, prospective, single-arm clinical trial evaluating the safety and efficacy of sequential adult left lateral lobe liver transplantation (SALT) in patients with liver cirrhosis and hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC). The study aims to assess the overall survival rate of patients with liver cirrhosis and HCC treated with SALT. The study includes 20 patients who meet the inclusion criteria, and the primary outcome measure is overall survival at 3 years after the second liver resection. Secondary outcome measures include disease-free survival, tumor-free survival period, and psychological or social conditions that may interfere with the patient's participation in the study or evaluation of the study results. The study is conducted at a single center in China, and the study population consists of adult patients aged 18-75 with liver cirrhosis and HCC infection caused by hepatitis B virus. The study excludes patients with combined main portal vein tumor thrombus, main vena cava tumor thrombus, and common bile duct tumor thrombus, as well as those with severe hepatic encephalopathy, pulmonary hypertension, or other conditions that may interfere with the patient's participation in the study or evaluation of the study results. The study intervention is sequential adult left lateral lobe liver transplantation, which involves a two-stage liver resection procedure, including hemihepatectomy combined with left lateral lobe liver transplantation and residual liver resection after the graft grows to a sufficient functional liver volume. The study results suggest that SALT may be a safe and effective treatment option for patients with liver cirrhosis and HCC, with a high overall survival rate and low disease-free survival rate.

[/INST]  The Absolute Flow for Ischemia With No Obstructive Coronary Arteries clinical trial aims to evaluate the diagnostic accuracy of continuous thermodilution in diagnosing microvascular coronary dysfunction in patients with stable angina. The study will prospectively validate the capacity of continuous thermodilution-measured coronary flow reserve (CFR) as a predictor of the presence of angina measured by the Seattle Angina Questionnaire (SAQ) at 3 months. The study will also identify hemodynamic factors related to the persistence of angina, clinical factors related to the persistence of angina, establish the prevalence of patients with coronary microvascular dysfunction within the cohort of INOCA patients, and identify predictors of major cardiovascular events at 12 months. The study will evaluate the concordance between measures of coronary microvascular function obtained by continuous thermodilution and bolus thermodilution, as well as their concordance with clinical characteristics.

The study will enroll patients aged 18 years or older with a clinical indication for coronary angiography and in whom the use of microvascular function diagnosis by pressure guide is considered clinically necessary. Exclusion criteria include decompensated heart failure or cardiogenic shock, admission due to acute coronary syndrome with an elevation of markers in the month prior to inclusion, indication for coronary angioplasty, severe pulmonary hypertension, obstructive hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, severe valvular disease, and previous allergy or intolerance to adenosine or adenosine triphosphate.

The study will be designed as an observational, prospective, and multicenter study. Participants will undergo coronary angiography and continuous thermodilution-measured CFR and minimal microvascular resistance (MMR) flow will be obtained. The primary outcome measure will be the angina status assessed by the Seattle Angina Questionnaire (SAQ) at inclusion. Secondary outcome measures will include quality of life at 3 months, accuracy of continuous thermodilution-measured CFR, and prevalence of patients with coronary microvascular dysfunction.

The study will provide valuable insights into the diagnostic accuracy of continuous thermodilution in diagnosing microvascular coronary dysfunction in patients with stable angina, and will help to identify predictors of major cardiovascular events at 12 months. The study will also contribute to the understanding of the pathological value of CFR and MMR flow in the diagnosis of coronary microvascular dysfunction.

[/INST]  The provided clinical trial document outlines an open-label, randomized, monocenter trial titled "Acupuncture for Nasal Congestion in Allergic Rhinitis: An Open-Label, Randomized, Monocenter Trial (ANCAR Trial)." The study aims to evaluate the effects of an acupuncture treatment protocol on nasal congestion in patients with allergic rhinitis (AR).

The study will enroll 100 participants diagnosed with AR, aged 18-70 years, with a VAS nasal congestion score of 3-10. Participants will be randomly assigned to either the acupuncture arm or the control arm (Carelastin®). The acupuncture arm will receive a fixed set of acupuncture points, while the control arm will receive Carelastin® (azelastine nasal spray).

The primary outcome measure will be the VAS nasal congestion score at the end of the 6-week treatment period. Secondary outcome measures will include VAS nasal congestion scores at different time points during the study, Peak Nasal Inspiratory Flow (PNIF), Adapted Nasal Obstruction Symptom Evaluation (NOSE), Visual Analog Scale (VAS) scores for other nasal and ocular signs and symptoms, general health, concentration, and energy level, and equalization of middle ear pressure in the case of patients who fly and/or dive.

The study will be conducted at a single center in the Netherlands, and the results will be analyzed using descriptive statistics and inferential statistics. The study hypothesizes that acupuncture will improve nasal congestion in AR compared to Carelastin®.

In conclusion, the ANCAR trial aims to evaluate the safety and efficacy of acupuncture in improving nasal congestion in patients with allergic rhinitis. The study will provide valuable insights into the potential benefits of acupuncture as a treatment option for nasal congestion in AR, and may lead to increased acceptance of acupuncture as a solid treatment option in clinical practice.

The study aims to assess the feasibility of a randomized controlled trial (RCT) investigating the effects of dietary supplements, including fish oil and probiotics, on the maternal gut microbiome and mental health outcomes in pregnant women with a history of anxiety and/or depression.

The study will recruit 100 pregnant women, aged 18-43 years, who are currently stable but have a history of anxiety and/or depression. Participants will be randomly assigned to one of four study groups: (1) Gutopia (dietary modification, fish oil, and probiotics), (2) Gutboost (probiotic and fish oil supplements), (3) Gutless (fish oil and placebo probiotic), or (4) Active Comparator (standard care by obstetrician with a one-time dietary consult).

The primary outcome measures for the study include feasibility, measured by the time taken to recruit 100 participants and successfully randomize/assign 25 participants per study arm, as well as adherence to supplement intake, adherence to dietary protocol, completion of study visits, and study obstacles. Secondary outcome measures include mental health scores using EPDS and GAD7 scales, and stool sample collection.

Keywords related to the study include "Gut Microbiome," "Gut-Brain Axis," "Diet," "Omega 3 Fatty acids," "Probiotics," "Fish Oil," "Mental Health disorders," "Perinatal Depression and anxiety."

[/INST]  The study is designed to investigate the diagnostic and prognostic role of serum amyloid A (SAA) in intrathoracic sarcoidosis. The study will enroll patients with newly diagnosed intrathoracic sarcoidosis and healthy controls. The primary outcome measures will include the correlation of SAA concentrations in patients with those in healthy controls, as well as the correlation of SAA concentrations with other biomarkers of granulomatous inflammation and pulmonary interstitial disease. Additionally, the study will assess the correlation of SAA concentrations with pulmonary function test results, radiologic extent of disease, and changes in lung function tests after 3 years of follow-up. Finally, the study will investigate the correlation of SAA concentrations with the need for recent/ongoing therapy after 3 years of follow-up.

[/INST]  The provided clinical trial document pertains to a randomized, single-blind, multicenter controlled trial investigating the benefit of early intrauterine transfer of blank culture medium prior to transfer of a thawed embryo from the first in vitro fertilization (IVF) cycle. The study aims to determine whether the early transfer of blank culture medium improves the clinical pregnancy rate compared to a sham transfer.

The study includes 150 participants who are undergoing their first IVF cycle and have at least two eligible embryos for transfer or freezing. The participants are randomly assigned to either the experimental group (blank culture transfer) or the sham comparison group (no transfer). The primary outcome measure is the clinically progressive pregnancy rate between the two groups, which is measured using first-trimester ultrasound at 12 weeks of amenorrhea. Secondary outcome measures include the occurrence of pregnancy, biochemical pregnancy, clinical pregnancy, early miscarriage, live birth, and differential cost-result ratio.

The study plan involves a randomized, parallel assignment design with single masking. The arms and interventions are as follows:

* Experimental: With blank culture (procedure: Blank culture transfer; maximum of 0.1 ml of gassed embryo culture medium preheated to 37°C is injected into the uterine cavity transcervically using an embryo transfer catheter placed just beyond the internal os, two to 3 days before transfer of the thawed embryo)
* Sham Comparator: Without blank culture (procedure: Sham transfer; an intermediate transfer step is added two or three days before the planned transfer of the frozen embryo but with an empty catheter)

The study measures the primary outcome at 12 weeks of amenorrhea and secondary outcome measures at various time points, including day 14 and end of study (year 3). The study also evaluates the total estimated expenditure for the two care strategies compared using a budget impact analysis over a one-year time horizon.

[/INST]  The study is a multicenter, observational, and controlled cohort study aimed at evaluating the prognostic risk factors and long-term health impact of immunotherapy in patients with primary solid malignant cancers. The study includes patients who are receiving immunotherapy for the first time and are aged between 18 and 80 years old. The study collects baseline information before treatment, including demographic characteristics, tumor and anti-tumor history, quality of life scores, and blood sample collection information. Follow-up information after treatment, including progression-free survival (PFS), total survival period (OS), and scoring results of various questionnaires (PHQ-9, etc.), is also collected. The study aims to provide high-level evidence-based medical evidence for the selection of immunotherapy schemes for these patients, precise prevention and health management of adverse reactions after immunotherapy, and further improvement of survival prognosis of patients.

The study includes 3 arms:

* Arm 1: Solid tumor patients receiving immunotherapy for the first time
* Arm 2: Solid tumor patients receiving immunotherapy combined with other treatments
* Arm 3: Solid tumor patients receiving other immunotherapy treatments

The study excludes patients with previous medical history of other malignant tumors, liver/lung metastasis, no pathology certificate, having received ICIs or other immunotherapy in the past, and participating in clinical research in the past.

The study plan includes the following steps:

1. Baseline information collection before treatment
2. Follow-up information collection after treatment
3. Data analysis to summarize factors that may affect the efficacy and prognosis of patients receiving immunotherapy.

The primary outcome measures of the study include progression-free survival (PFS), total survival period (OS), and scoring results of various questionnaires (PHQ-9, etc.).

[/INST]  This clinical trial aims to evaluate the effectiveness of confidential social network referrals for HIV testing in Moshi, Tanzania. The study will randomly assign participants to either the experimental group, which will receive both CONSORT referrals and card referrals, or the active comparator group, which will receive card referrals alone. The primary outcome measure will be the uptake of HIV testing, measured by the number of referred clients who present for testing at participating study sites within 30 days of the testing offer. The study will be designed as a health services research project with a randomized parallel assignment design, and will not mask the participants or the study staff. The study will include adult participants who are literate and live, work, or regularly receive care in Moshi, Tanzania, and will not accept healthy volunteers. The study will begin once the participant group and arm allocation are determined, and the data will be collected within 30 days of the time of the testing offer.

[/INST]  The provided clinical trial document pertains to a study titled "Tele-education in Patients With a Moderate Depressive Episode in Primary Care." The study aims to evaluate the effectiveness of a tele-education program in improving medication adherence and reducing barriers to treatment in patients with moderate depression in primary care settings.

The study design is a single-centered randomized controlled trial with parallel assignment and no masking. Participants will be randomly assigned to either the experimental group (tele-education program) or the control group (usual care). The primary outcome measure will be the rate of maintenance on continuous antidepressant medication at 6 months after inclusion in the study, measured using healthcare reimbursement data. Secondary outcome measures include changes in feelings of self-efficacy and barriers to treatment using self-questionnaires completed via the digital platform at inclusion and 3 months post inclusion.

The tele-education program consists of 5 individual remote sessions, each lasting an average of 60 minutes, scheduled every week for 5 weeks. The sessions will cover various topics related to depression, including educational diagnosis, personalized hygienic and dietary measures, identification of symptoms, and the role of family and friends. The program is designed to adapt to changes in depressive symptoms over time.

The study includes 100 participants, aged 18 years or older, with a moderate depressive episode according to the DSM-V criteria. Exclusion criteria include patients who are unable to complete self-questionnaires, have already undergone a psycho-education or therapeutic patient education program regarding depression, or require follow-up by a psychiatrist.

The study's keywords are "psychoeducation."

[/INST]  The provided clinical trial document outlines a Phase 1/Phase 2 open-label study to evaluate the safety, tolerability, and efficacy of SAR444836, an adeno-associated viral vector-mediated gene transfer of human phenylalanine hydroxylase, in adult participants with phenylketonuria (PKU). The study will enroll adult males and females aged 18-65 years old, and will consist of a single dose of SAR444836 administered via intravenous infusion. The primary outcome measures will include the incidence of treatment-emergent adverse events (TEAEs) and the proportion of participants with sustained plasma levels of Phe below 360 μmol/L for at least 4 weeks without dietary Phe restriction at Week 24 and Week 96 or end of study. Secondary outcome measures will include changes in plasma Phe levels, dietary protein intake, and the proportion of participants with sustained plasma levels of Phe below 600 μmol/L and 120 μmol/L, as well as changes in plasma Phe:Tyr ratio. The study will also assess the duration of viral vector shedding in urine, saliva, and semen samples collected at 4-week intervals following SAR444836 administration. The study is designed as a single-group assignment with no masking, and will be conducted over a period of 96 weeks or end of study.

[/INST]  The clinical trial aims to evaluate the diagnostic accuracy of pseudo-continuous arterial spin labeling (pCASL) as a substitute for fluorodeoxyglucose-position emission tomography (FDG-PET) in patients with mild cognitive impairment (MCI) and subjective cognitive decline (SCD). The primary outcome measures include the correlation between brain hypoperfusion and brain hypometabolism at baseline, and the correlation between brain hypoperfusion patterns and amyloid and tau status. Secondary outcome measures include differences in brain perfusion indices among patients with different amyloid and tau status, correlations between brain hypoperfusion and neuropsychological tests, predictive properties of brain hypoperfusion and brain hypometabolism for conversion to dementia, and correlations between brain hypoperfusion and CSF and blood biomarkers. The study will enroll patients aged 18-80 years with MCI or SCD, and will be conducted at the Centre Hospitalier Valida. The study plan includes a diagnostic test using pCASL and brain 3 Tesla MRI, and the study will be conducted over a period of 2 years.

[/INST]  The study aims to evaluate the effectiveness of an active break intervention on reducing low back pain and musculoskeletal discomfort in young people who spend most of their time sitting. The study will randomize 50 participants into either an experimental group (receiving active break recommendations) or a control group (receiving self-care recommendations). The primary outcome measures will include pain intensity, disability, perceived musculoskeletal discomfort during prolonged sitting, and global perceived effect. Secondary outcome measures will include post-intervention questionnaire results. [/INST]  The provided clinical trial document pertains to a phase II study investigating the effects of Lysergic Acid Diethylamide (LSD) in palliative care. The study aims to evaluate the safety and efficacy of LSD in reducing anxiety, pain, and improving quality of life in patients with end-stage fatal diseases.

The study is a randomized, double-blind, active-placebo-controlled trial, with two arms: experimental and active comparator. Participants will receive either LSD or a placebo, and the primary outcome measures include changes in state anxiety, pain levels, and spiritual well-being. Secondary outcome measures include changes in demoralization, quality of life, and adverse events.

The study includes 115 participants, aged 25 years or older, with end-stage fatal diseases and a life expectancy of 12 weeks to 2 years. Exclusion criteria include a history of hypersensitivity to LSD, current use of potent drug CYP2D6 inhibitors, and unwillingness to comply with the washout period.

The study measures various outcomes, including changes in state anxiety, pain levels, and spiritual well-being, using questionnaires and ratings from participants, caregivers, and investigators. The study also assesses the associations between acute LSD effects and long-lasting therapeutic effects, as well as the expectancy as a mediator for treatment effects.

The study duration is up to 9 weeks after the second intervention, and the primary outcome measures will be assessed at baseline, 2 days after each intervention, and 2 weeks after the second intervention. Secondary outcome measures will be assessed at various time points throughout the study duration.

Adverse events will be monitored throughout the study duration, and vital signs will be measured before and up to 12 hours after drug administration. The study includes qualitative interviews and community observer ratings to assess patient behavior and attitudes.

In summary, the study aims to evaluate the safety and efficacy of LSD in palliative care, with the primary outcome measures focusing on reducing anxiety, pain, and improving quality of life in patients with end-stage fatal diseases.
